Tutorial on the NBA: Are you paid to win?¶

Introduction

The NBA is a multi-billion dollar industry, having world-reknown players as household names, like Michael Jordan, LeBron James, and Stephen Curry. Throughout history we've seen our fair share of basketball icons, incredibly-performing players, and even badly-performing players. However, just because a player performs well or badly, does that mean that they'll be paid appropriately per their skills? In this tutorial, we will explore this.

For this tutorial, we will be analyzing NBA Players and Salaries and if having a greater salary will correlate to a player contributing to more wins.

We hypothesize that having a greater salary will correlate to a player contributing to more wins.

Data Collection/Curation¶

salaries = pd.read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/jaffeh/cmsc320_fproject_files/main/salaries_1985to2018.csv")

In the players dataset, there are 25 columns:

  • index
  • _id: unique id to identify player
  • birthDate
  • birthPlace
  • career_AST: Assists throughout career
  • career_FG%: Field goal percentage for their career
  • career_FG3%: Field goal for three's percentage for their career
  • career_FT%: Free throw percentage throughout career
  • career_G: Games played throughout career
  • career_PER: Player efficiency rating for their career
  • career_PTS: Player's points throughout career
  • career_TRB: Player's total rebounds for their career
  • career_WS: Player's win share (contribution to a win) during their career
  • career_eFG%: Player's effective field goal percentage for their career
  • college
  • draft_pick: order in which they were picked for a team during draft
  • draft_round: which round they got drafted in
  • draft_team: which team they got drafted to
  • draft_year: which year they got drafted
  • height
  • highSchool
  • name
  • position: which position in basketball the player plays
  • shoots: which hand they shoot from
  • weight

Non-descriptory column titles are self explanatory.

The players dataset has two columns that will be useful for our analysis: "career_PER" and "career_WS" (player efficiency rating and win shares); primarily career win shares, though.

In [5]:
#Combine players and salaries dataset
combined_df = players.merge(salaries, left_on='_id', right_on='player_id')
combined_df = combined_df.drop('league', axis=1)
combined_df = combined_df.drop('season_end', axis=1)
combined_df = combined_df.drop('season_start', axis=1)
combined_df = combined_df.drop('player_id', axis=1)
combined_df = combined_df.drop(combined_df.loc[:, 'career_eFG%':'weight'].columns, axis=1)
combined_df = combined_df.drop(combined_df.loc[:, 'birthDate':'career_G'].columns, axis=1)
combined_df = combined_df.drop(combined_df.loc[:, 'career_PTS':'career_TRB'].columns, axis=1)
combined_df = combined_df.drop('index_y', axis=1)

One similarity between the distributions is they both have a noticeable left tail.

Right off the bat, from these results we can observe that for the players with the mode salary, or most frequently appearing/most common salary, the career win shares of these players vary greatly. The same can be said about the career win shares for players with the median salary, or midpoint of the salaries.

We can further examine this by looking at the average/mean win share of players with the most common salary and midpoint salary, and the range of the salaries.

For further analysis, it's important to note mean, median, and mode are all measures of central tendency, which means a value meant to be representative of the data.

For the players with the most common salary, it's seen that the average amount of career win shares is about 42.8. However, the players' win shares vary from -0.8 to 214.0, a very stark range.

For the players with the midpoint salary, it's seen that the average amount of career win shares is about 37.7. However, the players' win shares vary from -0.5 to 234.6, also a very vast range.

This can be interpreted as that when MODE or MEDIAN is used as the measure of central tendency in the context of player salaries, when seeing if it's representative of a relationship between salary and win shares for this dataset when examining their corresponding player career win shares, it's hard to support if there is a relationship considering the massive range between their respective maximum and minimum career win shares.

How does this compare to the general statistics of win shares?

Comparing the summary statistics demonstrates the following:

  • The player paid the average amount has a higher career win share than the average career win share of all the players
  • The players paid the most common amount have a higher career win share (on average) than the most common career win share among all players
  • The players paid the midpoint amount have a higher career win share (on average) than the midpoint career win share amount all players
  • The player paid the least has a higher win share than the player(s) with the lowest win share
  • The player paid the most has a lower win share than the player(s) with the highest win share

As we can tell from these observations and analysis, in the context of our question on if having a greater salary will correlate to a player contributing to more wins, having a certain salary does not mean they'll corroborate with having a corresponding statistic career win share. For example, having the highest salary doesn't mean the highest win share, and having the lowest salary doesn't mean the lowest win share.

Examining our question over time periods can help analyze if the answer is consistent or varies over time.

Let's see if having a greater salary will correlate to a player contributing to more wins during each of the following time periods:

# Create salary, winshare, and player ID arrays for plotting
x = highest_paid['Total Win Shares'].array
y = highest_paid['Total Salary'].array

# Get linear regression stats for winshares vs. salary
slope, intercept, r, p, std_err = stats.linregress(x, y)

# Using slope and intercept stats, get y values for the line of linear regression by running x values through
# slope-intercept formula 
def myfunc(x):
  return slope * x + intercept
mymodel = list(map(myfunc, x))

# Plot salary vs. winshares and draw best fit line
plt.scatter(x, y)
plt.plot(x, mymodel)

# Add title and axis labels

plt.ylabel("Player Salary")
plt.xlabel("Career Winshare")

# Label each point on the plot with the corresponding player ID
for i, txt in enumerate (n):
    plt.text(x[i], y[i], txt)

plt.show()

One extenuating factor that could affect a player's salary that we can explore is time. Using pandas, we can sort our dataframe by season and then calculate the total payroll for ALL players in each season and average that value out. A trend line is not even needed to see that average total payroll increases steadily over time. Clearly, the time period affects how well a player is paid. Lets think about the top ten winshares data frame. One player who makes that list is Michael Jordan, who was in his prime during the '90s. However, he does not make the top 10 highest paid players list because he played during a time period where the NBA did not pay their players as well, relative to more recent seasons. Total win share is a pretty good quantitative metric for a player's skill. As shown by this plot, skill is not the only factor that determine's a player's salary, though it definitely plays a role. Lets find the correlation coefficient for season and salary to figure out if time is a better predictor of salary than winshare/skill. To do this, we will need to change the datatype of the "season" column, which is currently a string.

# Loop through array of seasons, truncate string at "-", convert to float
idx = 0
for s in x:
    s = s.split("-")
    x[idx] = float(s[0])
    idx +=1

# Get linear regression stats for average total payroll vs. year
slope, intercept, r, p, std_err = stats.linregress(x.astype(float), y)

# Using slope and intercept stats, get y values for the line of linear regression 
# by running x values through slope-intercept formula 
def myfunc(x):
  return slope * x + intercept
mymodel = list(map(myfunc, x))

# Print coefficient of correlation
print(r)

0.9713006158162731

Wow! The coefficient of correlation has a value of 0.97! The value of r is very close to 1, which makes the year/time period a very close-to-perfect predictor of a player's salary. Now we can conclude that time is certainly a much better predictor of a player's salary than their skill.

Hypothesis Testing¶

To see if our hypothesis that having a greater salary will correlate to a player contributing to more wins, we can do hypothesis testing.

First, we will do a Pearson's Correlation Coefficient test, which can help us see if there's a linear relationship/correlation between salary and career win share.

In [31]:
from scipy.stats import pearsonr
sal_data = combined_df['salary']
ws_data = list(map(float, (combined_df['career_WS'])))
stat1, p1 = pearsonr(sal_data, ws_data)
print('stat=%.3f, p=%.3f' % (stat1, p1))
if p1 <= 0.05:
 print('Likely dependent')
else:
 print('Likely independent')

stat=0.464, p=0.000
Likely dependent

Null Hypothesis: the two sets are independent

Alternative Hypothesis: there's a dependency between the sets

Based on the pearson's correlation coefficient test, the p-value is less than 0.05, meaning there is insufficient evidence to prove the null hypothesis that salary and career win share are independent of each other, therefore this test indicates they are likely dependent on each other, in other words a (linear) relationship. The positive statistic also indicates it's a positive linear relationship.

Let's do some more testing; below we are doing a Kendalls Rank Correlation, which tests for a monotonic relationship between the variables.

In [32]:
from scipy.stats import kendalltau
stat2, p2 = kendalltau(sal_data, ws_data)
print('stat=%.3f, p=%.3f' % (stat2, p2))
if p2 <= 0.05:
 print('Likely dependent')
else:
 print('Likely independent')

stat=0.363, p=0.000
Likely dependent

Null Hypothesis: the two sets are independent

Alternative Hypothesis: there's a dependency between the sets

Based on the Kendalls Rank Correlation test, the p-value is less than 0.05, meaning there is insufficient evidence to prove the null hypothesis that salary and career win share are independent of each other, therefore this test indicates they are likely dependent on each other, in other words a (monotonic) relationship. The positive statistic also indicates it's a positive monotonic relationship.

Let's do another test to corroborate or deaffirm this; Spearmans Rank Correlation test will be performed below, which tests for a monotonic relationship between variables.

In [33]:
from scipy.stats import spearmanr
stat3, p3 = spearmanr(sal_data, ws_data)
print('stat=%.3f, p=%.3f' % (stat3, p3))
if p3 <= 0.05:
 print('Likely dependent')
else:
 print('Likely independent')

stat=0.519, p=0.000
Likely dependent

Null Hypothesis: the two sets are independent

Alternative Hypothesis: there's a dependency between the sets

Based on the Spearmans Rank Correlation test, the p-value is less than 0.05, meaning there is insufficient evidence to prove the null hypothesis that salary and career win share are independent of each other, therefore this test indicates they are likely dependent on each other, in other words a (monotonic) relationship. The positive statistic also indicates it's a positive monotonic relationship.

In summary, based on our hypothesis testing, results indicate that our hypothesis that having a greater salary will correlate to a player contributing to more wins has evidence to support it. All the tests indicate that there is a relationship/dependency between salary and career win shares, with the Kendalls Rank Correlation test and the Spearmans Rank Correlation specifically indicating a monotonic relationship, in other words the relationship/correlation observed is that as salary increases, so does career win share for that player.

Communication of Insights Attained¶

There is one certain trend that salary increases as a measure of time. Moreover, our analysis over time indicates that the time period has more of an impact on player salary than "skill" or advanced statistics such as Win Shares or an Efficiency Rating. Using the Pearson's Correlation Coefficient test and the Spearmans Rank Correlation test we are able to deduce that most of the time, a greater salary is correlated to a player contributing to more wins. This is shown through Career Win Shares. Initially, our analysis of mode, median, and average players shows that the highest paid player would not have the highest win share. This is evident, but we have found that rather there is a general correlation rather than absolute.

In conclusion, if teams are to pay a player more, it is likely that the said player will contribute to winning more, or have a higher efficiency rating(as shown in initial analysis). Furthermore, salary is not an absolute measure, but a general tendency of what a team is willing to spend to be able to acquire talent. This is shown by household names such as Kobe Bryant, Lebron James, and Chris Bosh. These are players with Win Shares that significantly contributed to winning, and had the salary to back it up.
